<subSubSection id="C34B656BFFB70A6DFD8B00B2DEAD6C35" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEE36E0FFB70A6CFD8B00B2D9D26E3C" blockId="36.[533,1536,1769,1897]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB70A6CFD8B00B2DE246E54" authority="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw, 2019" authorityName="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw" authorityYear="2019" box="[533,585,1770,1793]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Mini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="36" pageNumber="24" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB70A6CFD8B00B2DE246E54" box="[533,585,1770,1793]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Mini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
adds a ninth genus to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB70A6CFCC000B1DFB56E54" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1889" box="[862,984,1769,1793]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cophylinae">Cophylinae</taxonomicName>
for a unique clade of miniaturised frogs that falls sister to the large-bodied 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB70A6CFCBF0154DFA16E71" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1882" box="[801,972,1804,1828]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Plethodontohyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB70A6CFCBF0154DFA16E71" box="[801,972,1804,1828]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Plethodontohyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="136A2A65FFB70A6CFC450153D8626E76" box="[987,1039,1803,1827]" captionStart="Fig 1" captionStartId="2.[192,220,1354,1373]" captionTargetBox="[192,1536,208,1332]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[192,1536,208,1332]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig 1. Stylised representation of the latest phylogeny of the microhylid subfamily Cophylinae. Based on the phylogenetic tree of Tu et al. [20] (reconstructed from a concatenated multi-gene DNA sequence data set) with numerous nomenclatural updates. See that paper for support values and phylogenetic context. The sister species of Rhombophryne proportionalis sp. nov. is an undescribed candidate species (R. sp. Ca7) that is not included in this phylogeny; its taxonomy will be treated elsewhere. Taxa highlighted in red are those described herein. Inset photos show a selection of the new species described herein, and representatives of the other small-bodied genera, Stumpffia and Anilany. Inset photos are not to scale. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0213314.g001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614085/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig 1</figureCitation>
). Although body size is the most obvious character that differentiates these two sister genera, they are also distinguished by a number of osteological features, and can be identified without skeletal analysis by their digital reduction
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEE36E0FFB60A6DFD8B0688DEAD6BFF" blockId="37.[533,1536,208,1376]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
(present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFD100689DEAF69BD" authority="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw, 2019" authorityName="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw" authorityYear="2019" box="[654,706,209,232]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Mini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="24" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFD100689DEAF69BD" box="[654,706,209,232]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Mini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFCAA0688DFB269BD" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1882" box="[820,991,208,232]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Plethodontohyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFCAA0688DFB269BD" box="[820,991,208,232]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Plethodontohyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and vomerine teeth (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFAAF0689D90869BD" authority="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw, 2019" authorityName="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw" authorityYear="2019" box="[1329,1381,209,232]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Mini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="24" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFAAF0689D90869BD" box="[1329,1381,209,232]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Mini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFD8B06ABDEAD685E" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1882" box="[533,704,243,267]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Plethodontohyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFD8B06ABDEAD685E" box="[533,704,243,267]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Plethodontohyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Despite these differences and consistent recovery of the two genera as being reciprocally monophyletic in genetic analyses, the uncorrected p-distances between these genera in the 3’ fragment of the 
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFCDE0760DFC7681A" box="[832,938,312,336]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">16S rRNA</emphasis>
mitochondrial gene analysed here are at first glance surprisingly small at 8.3–13.3% (these distances would be distinctly higher if insertions and deletions would be considered in their calculation). Nevertheless, we consider the differences between these clades sufficiently great and robust that we regard them as constituting separate genera. Aside from their morphological and osteological differentiation, a further argument for their classification in distinct genera comes from the strength of support for their sistergroup relationship; while the two clades here seen as genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFB0F0450D9516B75" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1882" box="[1169,1340,520,544]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Plethodontohyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFB0F0450D9516B75" box="[1169,1340,520,544]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Plethodontohyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFAEE0451D9C96B75" authority="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw, 2019" authorityName="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw" authorityYear="2019" box="[1392,1444,521,544]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Mini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="24" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFAEE0451D9C96B75" box="[1392,1444,521,544]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Mini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been placed sister to each other in most molecular analyses so far, support values for this grouping often were low, and typically lower than the respective support for each of the two clades. The clade stability criterion [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFC0D0428DFC16BDD" author="Vences M &amp; Guayasamin JM &amp; Miralles A &amp; de la Riva I." box="[915,940,624,648]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="201 - 44" part="3636" refId="ref25206" refString="36. Vences M, Guayasamin JM, Miralles A, de la Riva I. To name or not to name: Criteria to promote economy of change in Linnaean classification schemes. Zootaxa. 2013; 3636 (2): 201 - 44. https: // doi. org / 10. 11646 / zootaxa. 363 6.2. 1" title="To name or not to name: Criteria to promote economy of change in Linnaean classification schemes" type="journal article" year="2013">36</bibRefCitation>
] is therefore better served considering both clades as separate genera.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEE36E0FFB60A6DFDAB04EDDEAD6C35" blockId="37.[533,1536,208,1376]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
The relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFC9B04EEDF546B98" authority="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw, 2019" authorityName="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw" authorityYear="2019" box="[773,825,694,717]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Mini" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="24" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFC9B04EEDF546B98" box="[773,825,694,717]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Mini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFCC404EDD8686B98" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1882" box="[858,1029,693,717]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Plethodontohyla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFCC404EDD8686B98" box="[858,1029,693,717]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Plethodontohyla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is analogous to the relationship of 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFAEB04EDD9B16B98" box="[1397,1500,693,717]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFAEB04EDD9B16B98" box="[1397,1500,693,717]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFD8B0480DED86BA5" box="[533,693,728,752]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFD8B0480DED86BA5" box="[533,693,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: a genus-level sister clade of miniaturised frogs (although 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFA820480D9EE6BA5" box="[1308,1411,728,752]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFA820480D9EE6BA5" box="[1308,1411,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also contains several non-miniaturised species), recovered in robust genetic phylogenies as reciprocally monophyletic, and distinguished by several diagnostic characters [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFB4A0545D8806A60" author="Rakotoarison A &amp; Scherz MD &amp; Glaw F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Andreone F &amp; Franzen M" box="[1236,1261,797,821]" journalOrPublisher="Vertebrate Zoology." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="271 - 398" part="67" refId="ref23849" refString="14. Rakotoarison A, Scherz MD, Glaw F, Kohler J, Andreone F, Franzen M, et al. Describing the smaller majority: Integrative taxonomy reveals twenty-six new species of tiny microhylid frogs (genus Stumpffia) from Madagascar. Vertebrate Zoology. 2017; 67 (3): 271 - 398." title="et al. Describing the smaller majority: Integrative taxonomy reveals twenty-six new species of tiny microhylid frogs (genus Stumpffia) from Madagascar" type="journal article" year="2017">14</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFB640545D97E6A60" author="Scherz MD &amp; Vences M &amp; Rakotoarison A &amp; Andreone F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Glaw F" box="[1274,1299,797,821]" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="372 - 81" part="100" refId="ref23908" refString="15. Scherz MD, Vences M, Rakotoarison A, Andreone F, Kohler J, Glaw F, et al. Reconciling molecular phylogeny, morphological divergence and classification of Madagascan narrow-mouthed frogs (Amphibia: Microhylidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution. 2016; 100: 372 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 20 16.04. 0 19 PMID: 270856 71" title="et al. Reconciling molecular phylogeny, morphological divergence and classification of Madagascan narrow-mouthed frogs (Amphibia: Microhylidae)" type="journal article" year="2016">15</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFA810545D9556A60" author="Scherz MD &amp; Vences M &amp; Rakotoarison A &amp; Andreone F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Glaw F" box="[1311,1336,797,821]" journalOrPublisher="Salamandra." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="479 - 83" part="53" refId="ref24479" refString="23. Scherz MD, Vences M, Rakotoarison A, Andreone F, Kohler J, Glaw F, et al. Lumping or splitting in the Cophylinae (Anura: Microhylidae) and the need for a parsimony of taxonomic changes: a response to Peloso et al. (2017). Salamandra. 2017; 53 (3): 479 - 83." title="et al. Lumping or splitting in the Cophylinae (Anura: Microhylidae) and the need for a parsimony of taxonomic changes: a response to Peloso et al. (2017)" type="journal article" year="2017">23</bibRefCitation>
]. Peloso et al. [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFA470545D99F6A60" author="Peloso PLV &amp; Frost DR &amp; Richards SJ &amp; Rodrigues MT &amp; Donnellan S &amp; Matsui M" box="[1497,1522,797,821]" journalOrPublisher="Cladistics." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="113 - 40" part="32" refId="ref24199" refString="19. Peloso PLV, Frost DR, Richards SJ, Rodrigues MT, Donnellan S, Matsui M, et al. The impact of anchored phylogenomics and taxon sampling on phylogenetic inference in narrow-mouthed frogs (Anura, Microhylidae). Cladistics. 2016; 32 (2): 113 - 40. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / cla. 12118" title="et al. The impact of anchored phylogenomics and taxon sampling on phylogenetic inference in narrow-mouthed frogs (Anura, Microhylidae)" type="journal article" year="2016">19</bibRefCitation>
] argued for the lumping of 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFCB20518DFFE6A0D" box="[812,915,832,856]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFCB20518DFFE6A0D" box="[812,915,832,856]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFC010518D8526A0D" box="[927,1087,832,856]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFC010518D8526A0D" box="[927,1087,832,856]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and later also 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFB430518D95C6A0D" authorityName="Scherz, Vences, Rakotoarison, Andreone, Köhler, Glaw &amp; Crottini" authorityYear="2016" box="[1245,1329,832,856]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Anilany" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFB430518D95C6A0D" box="[1245,1329,832,856]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Anilany</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFADE0518D9346A0D" author="Peloso PLV &amp; Raxworthy CJ &amp; Wheeler WC &amp; Frost DR" box="[1344,1369,832,856]" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="56 - 64" part="111" refId="ref24408" refString="22. Peloso PLV, Raxworthy CJ, Wheeler WC, Frost DR. Nomenclatural stability does not justify recognition of paraphyletic taxa: A response to Scherz et al. (2016). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution. 2017; 111 (2017): 56 - 64. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2017.03. 0 16 PMID: 28336422" title="Nomenclatural stability does not justify recognition of paraphyletic taxa: A response to Scherz et al. (2016)" type="journal article" year="2017">22</bibRefCitation>
] into a single genus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFDC1053BDE926A2E" box="[607,767,867,891]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFDC1053BDE926A2E" box="[607,767,867,891]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In response, we showed that the initial argument for lumping was based on misidentified specimens [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFC1405DDDFCE6AC8" author="Scherz MD &amp; Vences M &amp; Rakotoarison A &amp; Andreone F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Glaw F" box="[906,931,901,925]" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="372 - 81" part="100" refId="ref23908" refString="15. Scherz MD, Vences M, Rakotoarison A, Andreone F, Kohler J, Glaw F, et al. Reconciling molecular phylogeny, morphological divergence and classification of Madagascan narrow-mouthed frogs (Amphibia: Microhylidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution. 2016; 100: 372 - 81. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 20 16.04. 0 19 PMID: 270856 71" title="et al. Reconciling molecular phylogeny, morphological divergence and classification of Madagascan narrow-mouthed frogs (Amphibia: Microhylidae)" type="journal article" year="2016">15</bibRefCitation>
], and subsequently incorrectly coded morphology, ignoring various unique diagnostic features of 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFB9D05F0D83A6A95" authorityName="Scherz, Vences, Rakotoarison, Andreone, Köhler, Glaw &amp; Crottini" authorityYear="2016" box="[1027,1111,936,960]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Anilany" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFB9D05F0D83A6A95" box="[1027,1111,936,960]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Anilany</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the relationships of particularly unstable taxa (most notably 
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFCA10593D87C6AB6" box="[831,1041,971,995]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFCA10593DFCB6AB6" box="[831,934,971,995]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Stumpffia</taxonomicName>
tridactyla
</emphasis>
) [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFBB70592D82F6AB7" author="Scherz MD &amp; Vences M &amp; Rakotoarison A &amp; Andreone F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Glaw F" box="[1065,1090,970,994]" journalOrPublisher="Salamandra." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="479 - 83" part="53" refId="ref24479" refString="23. Scherz MD, Vences M, Rakotoarison A, Andreone F, Kohler J, Glaw F, et al. Lumping or splitting in the Cophylinae (Anura: Microhylidae) and the need for a parsimony of taxonomic changes: a response to Peloso et al. (2017). Salamandra. 2017; 53 (3): 479 - 83." title="et al. Lumping or splitting in the Cophylinae (Anura: Microhylidae) and the need for a parsimony of taxonomic changes: a response to Peloso et al. (2017)" type="journal article" year="2017">23</bibRefCitation>
]. We revised the taxonomy of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFD8B05B5DE116D50" box="[533,636,1005,1029]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFD8B05B5DE116D50" box="[533,636,1005,1029]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, describing 26 new species, and providing a more robust phylogeny that resolved the phylogenetic position of 
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFC820248DF806D7D" box="[796,1005,1040,1064]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFC820248DFEE6D7D" box="[796,899,1040,1064]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Stumpffia</taxonomicName>
tridactyla
</emphasis>
[
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFC620248D8786D7D" author="Rakotoarison A &amp; Scherz MD &amp; Glaw F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Andreone F &amp; Franzen M" box="[1020,1045,1040,1064]" journalOrPublisher="Vertebrate Zoology." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="271 - 398" part="67" refId="ref23849" refString="14. Rakotoarison A, Scherz MD, Glaw F, Kohler J, Andreone F, Franzen M, et al. Describing the smaller majority: Integrative taxonomy reveals twenty-six new species of tiny microhylid frogs (genus Stumpffia) from Madagascar. Vertebrate Zoology. 2017; 67 (3): 271 - 398." title="et al. Describing the smaller majority: Integrative taxonomy reveals twenty-six new species of tiny microhylid frogs (genus Stumpffia) from Madagascar" type="journal article" year="2017">14</bibRefCitation>
]. Despite this progress, the Amphibian Species of the World database (ASW) currently continues to use the lumped taxonomy, in contrast to AmphibiaWeb and other researchers that have adopted our proposed taxonomy (e.g. [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFD800220DE5A6DC5" author="Tu N &amp; Yang M &amp; Liang D &amp; Zhang P." box="[542,567,1144,1168]" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="85 - 91" part="126" refId="ref24267" refString="20. Tu N, Yang M, Liang D, Zhang P. A large-scale phylogeny of Microhylidae inferred from a combined dataset of 121 genes and 427 taxa. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution. 2018; 126: 85 - 91. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 201 8.03. 0 36 PMID: 2964958 1" title="A large-scale phylogeny of Microhylidae inferred from a combined dataset of 121 genes and 427 taxa" type="journal article" year="2018">20</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFDDA0220DE306DC5" author="Feng Y-J &amp; Blackburn DC &amp; Liang D &amp; Hillis DM &amp; Wake DB &amp; Cannatella DC" box="[580,605,1144,1168]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the USA." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="5864 - E 70" part="114" refId="ref26052" refString="53. Feng Y-J, Blackburn DC, Liang D, Hillis DM, Wake DB, Cannatella DC, et al. Phylogenomics reveals rapid, simultaneous diversification of three major clades of Gondwanan frogs at the Cretaceous-Paleogene boundary. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the USA. 2017; 114 (29): E 5864 - E 70. https: // doi. org / 10.1073 / pnas. 17046 32114 PMID: 286739 70" title="et al. Phylogenomics reveals rapid, simultaneous diversification of three major clades of Gondwanan frogs at the Cretaceous-Paleogene boundary" type="journal article" year="2017">53</bibRefCitation>
]). The newly described 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFCC50220D8F96DC5" authorityName="Scherz &amp; Hutter &amp; Rakotoarison &amp; Riemann &amp; Rödel &amp; Ndriantsoa &amp; Glos &amp; Roberts &amp; Crottini &amp; Vences &amp; Glaw" authorityYear="2019" box="[859,1172,1144,1168]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" species="proportionalis">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFCC50220D8F96DC5" box="[859,1172,1144,1168]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne proportionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is the only miniaturised 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFD8B02C3DED86DE6" box="[533,693,1179,1203]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFD8B02C3DED86DE6" box="[533,693,1179,1203]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so far known, is highly distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFBDF02C3D8C56DE6" box="[1089,1192,1179,1203]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFBDF02C3D8C56DE6" box="[1089,1192,1179,1203]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, lacking, for example, the externally obvious digital reduction that is present in all miniaturised species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFAB202E5D9FE6D80" box="[1324,1427,1213,1237]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFAB202E5D9FE6D80" box="[1324,1427,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and differing in body shape and proportions [
<bibRefCitation id="EFC04B11FFB60A6DFC3102B8DFA56DAD" author="Rakotoarison A &amp; Scherz MD &amp; Glaw F &amp; Kohler J &amp; Andreone F &amp; Franzen M" box="[943,968,1248,1272]" journalOrPublisher="Vertebrate Zoology." pageId="37" pageNumber="38" pagination="271 - 398" part="67" refId="ref23849" refString="14. Rakotoarison A, Scherz MD, Glaw F, Kohler J, Andreone F, Franzen M, et al. Describing the smaller majority: Integrative taxonomy reveals twenty-six new species of tiny microhylid frogs (genus Stumpffia) from Madagascar. Vertebrate Zoology. 2017; 67 (3): 271 - 398." title="et al. Describing the smaller majority: Integrative taxonomy reveals twenty-six new species of tiny microhylid frogs (genus Stumpffia) from Madagascar" type="journal article" year="2017">14</bibRefCitation>
]. This demonstrates that even miniaturised 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFD8B035BDED86C4E" box="[533,693,1283,1307]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFD8B035BDED86C4E" box="[533,693,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species can be distinguished by external morphology from 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFAB7035BD9FD6C4E" box="[1321,1424,1283,1307]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFAB7035BD9FD6C4E" box="[1321,1424,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, providing still further support for the recognition of 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFBDF037DD88C6C68" box="[1089,1249,1317,1341]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Rhombophryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFBDF037DD88C6C68" box="[1089,1249,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Rhombophryne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFB70037DD9386C68" box="[1262,1365,1317,1341]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Stumpffia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFB70037DD9386C68" box="[1262,1365,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Stumpffia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C514D63FFB60A6DFA10037DD98F6C68" authorityName="Scherz, Vences, Rakotoarison, Andreone, Köhler, Glaw &amp; Crottini" authorityYear="2016" box="[1422,1506,1317,1341]" class="Amphibia" family="Microhylidae" genus="Anilany" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Anura" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B925EAF2FFB60A6DFA10037DD98F6C68" box="[1422,1506,1317,1341]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Anilany</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as separate genera.
</paragraph>
